<div class="comment_block">

<div class="content">
<p class="comment-head">
<span class="author" id="comment-2976031">David Alan Christopher
</span> 
<a href="#comment-2976031" title="Permalink to this comment"><span class="date">[22 August 2010 05:17 PM]</span></a>
</p>
<p>
<p>Fascinating article Mike. I'm a librarian and our lot faces a handful of data as well. We've been writing some Java and Ruby code lately for in-house data analysis and even some basic segmentation of our huge inventory.</p>

<p>We often need to pull content from external public websites (usually government and NPO's), which don't have any form of exportable data formats. We've started using a tool called Feedity - <a href="http://feedity.com" rel="nofollow"><a href="http://feedity.com" rel="nofollow">http://feedity.com</a></a> for that purpose. So far it's worked out pretty well as we've been able to "scrape" raw data as structured information from hundreds of public sources.</p>

<p>I bet this space will only grow as data becomes more and more important for organizations world-wide.</p>
</p>
</div>
</div> <!-- /comment_block -->





